abla}{T} is no longer a hungry operator; the operator is completely satisfied. It is indeed a physical vector having a meaning. It represents the spatial rate of change of T . The x -component of  oldsymbol{
abla}{T} is how fast T changes in the x -direction. What is the direction of the vector  oldsymbol{
abla}{T} ? We know that the rate of change of T in any direction is the component of  oldsymbol{
abla}{T} in that direction (see Eq. ( 2.15)). It follows that the direction of  oldsymbol{
abla}{T} is that in which it has the largest possible component—in other words, the direction in which T changes the fastest. The gradient of T has the direction of the steepest uphill slope (in T ).

